Definition 3.2. Problem 3.3.
Definition 1.1. A preorder is a set $P$ equipped with a graph $(\leq)\subseteq P^{2}$ such that for all $a,b,c\in P$ we have: • $a=b\enspace\implies\enspace(a\leq b\enspace\land\enspace b\leq a)$ (reflexivity) • $(a\leq b\enspace\land\enspace b\leq c)\enspace\implies\enspace a\leq c$ (transitivity) A pro-monoid (for preordered monoid) is a preorder $P$ equipped with a product denoted by concatenation and a unit $\epsilon\in P$ such that for all $a,b,c,d\in P$: • $a\ \epsilon=a=\epsilon\ a\quad\land\quad(a\ b)\ c=a\ b\ c=a\ (b\ c)$ (monoidality) • $(a\leq b\enspace\land\enspace c\leq d)\enspace\implies\enspace(a\ c\enspace% \leq\enspace b\ d)$ (precongruence)
Definition 2.11 (Carboni-Walters CarboniWalters87 ). A cartesian bicategory is a symmetric monoidal category enriched in partial orders such that: 1. every object is equipped with a special commutative Frobenius algebra, 2. the monoid and comonoid structure of each Frobenius algebra are adjoint, 3. every arrow is a lax comonoid homomorphism. A morphism of cartesian bicategories is a strong monoidal functor preserving the partial order, the monoid and the comonoid structure.
Definition 1.5. A pregroup grammar is a pair $G=(\Delta,I)$ where $\Delta\subseteq V\times P(B)$ is a relation called the dictionnary (or lexicon) and $I\subseteq B^{2}$ the graph of basic types and induced steps. We require the set $\Delta(w)=\set{t\in P(B)\ }{\ (w,t)\in\Delta}$ to be finite for every word $w\in V$ in the vocabulary and write $\Delta(u)=\set{t(0)\dots t(n-1)\ }{\ t\in P(B)^{n}\land\forall\ i<n\ \cdot\ t(% i)\in\Delta(u(i))}$ for $u\in V^{n}$. Given a sentence type $s\in P(B)$, the language generated by $G$ is given by: $\mathcal{L}(G,s)=\set{u\in List(V)\enspace}{\enspace\exists\ t\in\Delta(u)% \enspace\cdot\enspace t\leq s\in P(B)}$
Definition 2.1. Problem 2.2.
Definition 3.2. Let $A$ be a set and let $\theta$ be an $(n+1)$-ary operation on $A$. $\theta$ is called 2-associative if the equivalent conditions of Lemma 3.1 are satisfied.
Definition 3.13. A protomodular operation $\theta$ is called strict if the equivalent conditions of Lemma 3.12 are satisfied. If it is clear which protomodular operation we are dealing with, then the term ”strict” will be referred to an algebra.
Definition 7. [5, Def. 4.1] Given a semisimple Abelian category $\mathbf{D}$, a simple object $S\in\textnormal{Obj}(\mathbf{D})$ and an interval $I\subseteq\mathbb{R}$ we define the diagram $\chi_{I,S}\in\mathbf{D}^{(\mathbb{R},\leq)}$ as: $\displaystyle\chi_{I,S}(a)=\begin{cases}{}S&\text{if }a\in I\\ 0&\text{otherwise}\end{cases}$ and $\displaystyle\chi_{I,S}(a\leq b)=\begin{cases}{}\textnormal{Id}_{S}&\text{if }% a,b\in I\\ 0&\text{otherwise}\end{cases}$ When working in $\mathbf{D}^{(\{1,\dots,n\},\leq)}$ we abuse of the same notation and write: $\chi_{[b,d],S}=\underbrace{0\to\dots\to 0}_{[1,b-1]}\to\underbrace{S% \xrightarrow{Id}\dots\xrightarrow{Id}S}_{[b,d]}\to\underbrace{0\to\dots\to 0}_% {[d+1,n]}$ We say that a $F$ has finite type if $F=\bigoplus_{k\in K}\chi_{I_{k},S_{k}}$
Definition 3. Let $\mathbf{D}$ be a category. We say that a lower-bounded function $p:\textnormal{Morph}(\mathbf{D})\to\mathbb{Z}$ is a categorical persistence function if, for all $u_{1}\to u_{2}\to v_{1}\to v_{2}$, the following inequalities hold: 1. $p(u1\to v1)\leq p(u2\to v1)$ and $p(u2\to v2)\leq p(u2\to v1)$. 2. $p(u2\to v1)-p(u1\to v1)\geq p(u2\to v2)-p(u1\to v2)$.
Definition 5. Given $u<v\in\mathbb{R}\cup\{-\infty,+\infty\}$ we define the multiplicity of $u,v$ as the minimum of the following expression, over $I_{u},I_{v}$ disjoint connected neighborhoods of $u$ and $v$ respectively: $p_{F}(\sup(I_{u}),\inf(I_{v}))-p_{F}(\inf(I_{u}),\inf(I_{v}))-p_{F}(\sup(I_{u}% ),\sup(I_{v}))+p_{F}(\inf(I_{u}),\sup(I_{v}))$ We denote this quantity by $\mu(u,v)$. Whenever $\mu(u,v)>0$ we say $(u,v)$ is a cornerpoint. By convention in this definition we consider $p_{F}(u,v)=\min_{x,y}p_{F}(x,y)$ whenever either $u$ or $v$ is not finite.
Definition 2. Given a regular category $\mathbf{R}$ with terminal object pt, we say that a function $r:{\textnormal{Obj}}(\mathbf{R})\to\mathbb{Z}$ is fiber-wise if, for all regular epimorphism $B\overset{\phi}{\twoheadrightarrow}D$, we have the following equality: $r(B)-r(D)=\sum_{\iota\in\textnormal{Hom}({\textnormal{pt}},D)}(r(B\times_{D}^{% \iota}{\textnormal{pt}})-r({\textnormal{pt}}))$ where the $B\times_{D}^{\iota}{\textnormal{pt}}$ realizes the pullback: $\tikzcd B\times_{D}^{\iota}{\textnormal{pt}}\arrow[hookrightarrow]{r}{}\arrow[% swap,twoheadrightarrow]{d}{}&B\arrow[twoheadrightarrow]{d}{\phi}\\ {\textnormal{pt}}\arrow[hookrightarrow]{r}{\iota}&D$
Definition 4. [5, Def. 4.3] Let $F\in\mathbf{C}^{(\mathbb{R},\leq)}$. Let $I\subset{\mathbb{R}}$ be an interval. We say that $F$ is constant on $I$ if for all $a\leq b\in I$ we have $p_{F}(a,a)=p_{F}(a,b)=p_{F}(b,b)$. We call $a\in{\mathbb{R}}$ a regular value (resp. right- or left-regular) for $F$ if there is a connected neighborhood (resp. connected right or left neighborhood) $I\;\reflectbox{$\in$}\;a$ such that $F$ is constant on $I$. Otherwise we call $a$ a critical value. $F$ is tame if it has a finite number of critical values.
Definition 1. Let $\mathbf{R}$ be a regular category. Given a lower-bounded function $r:\textnormal{Obj}(\mathbf{R})\to\mathbb{Z}$, we say that $r$ is a rank function if: 1. For any monomorphism $A\hookrightarrow B$, $r(A)\leq r(B)$ 2. For any regular epimorphism $B\twoheadrightarrow D$, $r(B)\geq r(D)$ 3. For any pullback square: $\tikzcd A\arrow[hookrightarrow]{r}{\iota_{1}}\arrow[swap,twoheadrightarrow]{d}% {\pi_{1}}&B\arrow[twoheadrightarrow]{d}{\pi_{2}}\\ C\arrow[hookrightarrow]{r}{\iota_{2}}&D$ where $\iota_{1},\iota_{2}$ are monomorphisms and $\pi_{1},\pi_{2}$ are regular epimorphisms, the following inequality holds: $r(B)-r(A)\geq r(D)-r(C)$ We say that a rank function $r$ is strict if the inequalities in conditions 1 and 2 are strict unless the morphisms are invertible. If furthermore $\mathbf{R}$ has an initial object $\emptyset$ and $r(\emptyset)=0$, we say that $r$ is $0$-based. A ranked category $(\mathbf{R},r)$ is simply a regular category $\mathbf{R}$ equipped with a rank function $r$.
Definition 6. The persistence diagram $\mathcal{D}F$ associated with the persistence function $p_{F}$ is the multiset of its cornerpoints, along with all the diagonal points $\{(u,u)|u\in\mathbb{R}_{\geq 0}\}$ with infinite (countable) multiplicity.
Definition A.2.2 (Initial object). An object $\emptyset$ in a category $\mathbf{C}$ is initial if for any object $x\in\mathbf{C}$ there exists a unique morphism $\emptyset\xrightarrow{!}x$.
Definition A.3.1 (Regular epimorphism). An epimorphism that is the coequalizer of a parallel pair of morphism.
Definition A.3.5 (Abelian category). A category $\mathbf{C}$ is abelian if 1. it is pointed, i.e. $\mathbf{C}$ has a zero objet; 2. has binary products and binary coproducts; 3. every morphism has kernel and cokernel; 4. each monomorphism is a kernel and each epimorphism is a cokernel.
Definition 12. Let $\cal C$ be a coloring on a ranked category $(\mathbf{R},r)$. We say that $\cal C$ is tight if for any tame ${(\mathbb{R},\leq)}$-indexed diagrams $F,G$ the following equality holds: $d_{\mathbf{R}}(F,G)=d_{\cal C}({\cal D}F,{\cal D}G)$
Definition A.2.6 (Equalizer). Let $X,Y$ be objects of $\mathbf{C}$ and consider two morphisms $X\xrightarrow{f}Y$, $X\xrightarrow{g}Y$. An object $Q$, together with a morphism $Q\xrightarrow{q}Y$ is an equalizer if $f\circ q=g\circ q$. Moreover, the pair $(Q,q)$ must be universal, i.e. given another coequalizer $(Q^{\prime},q^{\prime})$, there exists a unique morphism $Q^{\prime}\xrightarrow{u}Q$ such that the following diagrams commutes. $\tikzcd Q\ar[r,"q"]&X\ar[r,shiftleft=.75ex,"f"]\ar[r,shiftright=.75ex,swap,"g"% ]&Y\\ Q^{\prime}\ar[ru,swap,"q^{\prime}"]\ar[u,denselydotted,"u"description]$ Thus, equalizers are unique up to isomorphism. Moreover, every equalizer is a monomorphism.
Definition 8. [5, Def. 3.4] We remind that given two ${(\mathbb{R},\leq)}$-indexed diagrams $F,G$, they are $\epsilon$-interleaved if there are natural transformations $\phi^{F}:F\to GT_{\epsilon}$ and $\phi^{G}:G\to FT_{\epsilon}$ such that: $\displaystyle(\phi^{G}T_{\epsilon})\phi^{F}=F\eta_{2\epsilon}$ and $\displaystyle(\phi^{F}T_{\epsilon})\phi^{G}=G\eta_{2\epsilon}$ The interleaving distance $d(F,G)$ is the infimum of all $\epsilon$ values such that $F$ and $G$ are $\epsilon$-interleaved.
Definition A.2.8 (Finitely (co)complete category). A category $\mathbf{C}$ is finitely complete if it has equalizers, a terimal object and binary products. Analogously, a category $\mathbf{C}$ is finitely cocomplete if it has coequalizers, an initial object and binary coproducts.
Definition A.1.2 (Monomorphism). Consider $X,Y\in{\textnormal{Obj}}(\mathbf{C})$. $f:X\to Y$ is a monomorphism if given the following diagram $\tikzcd Z\ar[r,shiftleft=.75ex,"g"]\ar[r,shiftright=.75ex,swap,"h"]&X\ar[r,"f"% ]&Y$ if $f\circ g=f\circ h$ then $g=h$.
Definition A.3.3 (Kernel). Let $\mathbf{C}$ be a category with zero morphism $\xi$ and $f:X\to Y$ a morphism. The kernel of $f$ is defined as the equalizer of $\xi$ and $f$.
Definition 10. A ranked category $(\mathbf{R},r)$ is tight if, for any tame ${(\mathbb{R},\leq)}$-indexed diagrams $F$ and $G$, the following equality holds: $d_{\mathbf{R}}(F,G)=d({\cal D}F,{\cal D}G)$
Definition A.2.4 (Product). Let $X,Y$ be objects of a category $\mathbf{C}$. The product of $X$ and $Y$ is the object $P$, along with morphisms $\pi_{X}:Z\to X$ and $\pi_{Y}:Z\to Y$, such that given another such $P^{\prime},\pi^{\prime}_{X},\pi^{\prime}_{y}$, we have a unique morphism $P^{\prime}\to P$ that makes the following diagram commute: $\tikzcd&P^{\prime}\ar[dr,"\pi^{\prime}_{X}"]\ar[d,denselydotted,"u"description% ]\ar[dl,swap,"\pi^{\prime}_{Y}"]\\ X&P\ar[r,swap,"\pi_{Y}"]\ar[l,"\pi_{X}"]&Y$ We denote the product $X\times Y$.
Definition A.3.7 (Semisimple category). An Abelian category is semisimple if all its objects are semisimple, i.e. each object can be written as a finite sum of simple objects.
Definition A.2.1 (Terminal object). An object pt in a category $\mathbf{C}$ is called terminal if there exists a unique morphism $x\xrightarrow{!}{\textnormal{pt}}$ for any object $x\in\mathbf{C}$. If it exists, the terminal object is unique, up to unique isomorphism. For instance, the point space pt is terminal in Top.
Definition A.2.9 (Pullback). Let $X,Y$ and $Z$ be objects of a category $\mathbf{C}$, and $X\xrightarrow{f}Z$, $Y\xrightarrow{g}Z$ morphisms. An object $P$ and the morphisms $P\xrightarrow{p_{1}}X$, $P\xrightarrow{p_{2}}Y$ is a pullback if the following diagram $\tikzcd P\arrow[rightarrow]{r}{p_{1}}\arrow[swap,rightarrow]{d}{p_{2}}&X\arrow% [rightarrow]{d}{f}\\ Y\arrow[rightarrow]{r}{g}&Z$ commutes and, given another such $P^{\prime},p_{1}^{\prime},p_{2}^{\prime}$ we have a unique morphism $P^{\prime}\xrightarrow{u}P$ that makes the following diagram commute: $\tikzcd P^{\prime}\arrow[drr,bendleft,"p_{1}^{\prime}"]\arrow[swap,ddr,% bendright,"p_{2}^{\prime}"]\arrow[dr,denselydotted,"u"description]&&\\ &P\arrow[r,"p_{1}"]\arrow[swap,d,"p_{2}"]&X\arrow[d,"f"]\\ &Y\arrow[r,"g"]&Z$ That is to say, the pullback is universal with respect to the diagram, and thus unique up to isomorphism. We denote it $X\times_{Z}Y$.
Definition 11. Given an index set $\Gamma$, we say that a ranked category $(\mathbf{R},r)$ is $\Gamma$-colorable if there exist ranked categories $(\mathbf{Q}_{\gamma},r_{\gamma})$ for $\gamma\in\Gamma$ and image-preserving functors ${\cal C}_{\gamma}:\mathbf{R}\to\mathbf{Q}_{\gamma}$ such that 1. the induced functor ${\cal C}:\mathbf{R}\to\prod_{\gamma\in\Gamma}\mathbf{Q}_{\gamma}$ is fully faithful; 2. for each $X\in{\textnormal{Obj}}(\mathbf{R})$, $r_{\gamma}(X)$ is $0$ for all but finitely many $\gamma\in\Gamma$ and: $r(X)=\sum_{\gamma\in\Gamma}r_{\gamma}({\cal C}_{\gamma}(X))$ We call such ${\cal C}$ a $\Gamma$-coloring and we say that $(\mathbf{R},r)$ is ${\cal C}$-colored.
Definition A.3.4 (Cokernel). Let $\mathbf{C}$ be a category with zero morphism $\xi$ and $f:X\to Y$ a morphism. The cokernel of $f$ is defined as the coequalizer of $\xi$ and $f$.
Definition A.2.5 (Coproduct). Let $X,Y$ be objects of a category $\mathbf{C}$. The coproduct of $X$ and $Y$ is the object $C$, along with morphisms $\iota_{X}:X\to C$ and $\iota_{Y}:Y\to C$, such that given another such $C^{\prime},\iota^{\prime}_{X},\iota^{\prime}_{Y}$, we have a unique morphism $C\to C^{\prime}$ that makes the following diagram commute: $\tikzcd&C\ar[dr,leftarrow,"\iota^{\prime}_{X}"]\ar[d,leftarrow,denselydotted,"% u"description]\ar[dl,leftarrow,swap,"\iota^{\prime}_{Y}"]\\ X&X\amalg Y\ar[r,leftarrow,swap,"\iota_{Y}"]\ar[l,leftarrow,"\iota_{X}"]&Y$ We denote the coproduct $X\amalg Y$.
Definition 9. Let $F,G$ be two tame ${(\mathbb{R},\leq)}$-indexed diagrams in $\mathbf{R}$ and ${\cal D}F,{\cal D}G$ their persistence diagrams. The bottleneck distance between the persistence diagrams is defined as $d({\cal D}F,{\cal D}G)=\inf_{\beta\in{\cal B}}\sup_{p\in{\cal D}(F)}\|p-\beta(% p)\|_{\infty},$ where ${\cal B}$ is the collection of all bijections between ${\cal D}F$ and ${\cal D}G$.
Definition A.3.2 (Regular category). A category $\mathbf{R}$ is regular if the following conditions hold: 1. $\mathbf{R}$ is finitely complete. 2. Given $X\xrightarrow{f}Y$ a morphism and its pullback $(P,p_{1},p_{2})$, then the coequalizer of $p_{1}$ and $p_{2}$ exists. 3. Given the pullback $\tikzcd R\arrow[rightarrow]{r}{}\arrow[swap,rightarrow]{d}{g}&X\arrow[% rightarrow]{d}{f}\\ Z\arrow[rightarrow]{r}{}&Y$ if $f$ is a regular epimorphism, so is $g$.
Definition A.2.3 (Zero object and pointed category). An object which is both initial and terminal is said zero object. A category $\mathbf{C}$ equipped with a zero object is said pointed.
Definition A.3.6 (Simple object). Let $\mathbf{C}$ be an Abelian category. An object $X\in{\textnormal{Obj}}(\mathbf{C})$ is simple if its only subobjects are $0$ and $X$.
Definition A.2.7 (Coequalizer). Let $X,Y$ be objects of $\mathbf{C}$ and consider two morphisms $X\xrightarrow{f}Y$, $X\xrightarrow{g}Y$. An object $Q$, together with a morphism $Y\xrightarrow{q}Q$ is a coequalizer if $q\circ f=q\circ g$. Moreover, the pair $(Q,q)$ must be universal, i.e. given another coequalizer $(Q^{\prime},q^{\prime})$, there exists a unique morphism $Q\xrightarrow{u}Q^{\prime}$ such that the following diagrams commutes. $\tikzcd X\ar[r,shiftleft=.75ex,"f"]\ar[r,shiftright=.75ex,swap,"g"]&Y\ar[r,"q"% ]\ar[dr,swap,"q^{\prime}"]&Q\ar[d,denselydotted,"u"description]\\ &&Q^{\prime}$ Thus, coequalizers are unique up to isomorphism. Moreover, every coequalizer is an epimorphism.
Definition A.1.1 (Epimorphism). Consider $X,Y\in{\textnormal{Obj}}(\mathbf{C})$. $f:X\to Y$ is an epimorphism if given the following diagram $\tikzcd X\ar[r,"f"]&Y\ar[r,shiftleft=.75ex,"g"]\ar[r,shiftright=.75ex,swap,"h"% ]&Z$ if $g\circ f=h\circ f$ then $g=h$.
Definition 3.8. An affine ${\mathsf{B}}$-scheme is an object of the category ${\mathsf{Aff}}_{\mathsf{B}}={\mathsf{Blp}}^{\text{op}}$, a ${\mathsf{B}}$-scheme an object of the category ${\mathsf{Sch}}_{\mathsf{B}}$ (see Definition 2.7).
Definition 2.3. Let ${\mathsf{G}}$ be a site. A presheaf $F\colon{\mathsf{G}}^{\text{\rm op}}\to{\mathsf{Set}}$ is said to be a sheaf if, for every covering $\mathcal{U}=\{U_{i}\to U\}_{i\in I}$, the restriction map $\operatorname{Hom}(h_{U},F)\to\operatorname{Hom}(h_{\mathcal{U}},F)$ is an isomorphism.
Definition A.9. [25, Def. 4.2] Let ${\mathsf{C}}$ be a site, ${\mathsf{F}}$ a category fibered over ${\mathsf{C}}$, and $\mathcal{U}=\{U_{i}\rightarrow U\}$ a covering in ${\mathsf{C}}$. Let be given a cleavage $K$ (see Definition A.3). An object with descent data ($\{\xi_{i}\},\{\phi_{ij}\}$) on $\mathcal{U}$ is a collection of objects $\xi_{i}\in\mathcal{F}(U_{i})$, together with isomorphisms $\phi_{ij}:pr^{\ast}_{1}\xi_{i}\simeq pr^{\ast}_{2}\xi_{j}$ in $\mathcal{F}(U_{i}\times_{U}U_{j})$ such that the following cocycle conditions is satisfied: $pr^{\ast}_{13}\phi_{ik}=pr^{\ast}_{12}\phi_{ij}\circ pr^{\ast}_{23}\phi_{jk}:% pr^{\ast}_{3}\xi_{k}\rightarrow pr^{\ast}_{1}\xi_{i}\quad\text{\rm for any % triple of indices $i,j,k$}\,.$ The isomorphisms $\phi_{ij}$ are called transition isomorphisms of the object with descent data. An arrow between objects with descent data $\{\alpha_{i}\}:(\{\xi_{i}\},\{\phi_{ij}\})\rightarrow(\{\eta_{i}\},\{\psi_{ij}\})$ is a collection of arrows $\alpha_{i}:\xi_{i}\rightarrow\eta_{i}$ in $\mathcal{F}(U_{i})$ with the property that for each pair of indices $i,j$ the diagram $\xymatrix{pr^{\ast}_{2}\xi_{j}\ar[r]^{pr^{\ast}_{2}\alpha_{j}}\ar[d]^{\phi_{ij% }}&pr^{\ast}_{2}\eta_{j}\ar[d]^{\psi_{ij}}\\ pr^{\ast}_{1}\xi_{i}\ar[r]_{pr^{\ast}_{1}\alpha_{i}}&pr^{\ast}_{1}\eta_{i}}$ commutes.
Definition 5.5. The category of ${{{\mathbb{F}}_{1}}}$-schemes with relations is the fibered product of the categories of $B$-schemes and that of ${{\mathbb{F}}_{1}}$-schemes over the category of monoidal schemes. Thus, a ${\mathsf{B}}$-scheme $\Sigma$ generating the pair $(\underline{\Sigma},\Sigma_{\mathbb{Z}})$ and an ${{\mathbb{F}}_{1}}$-scheme $(\underline{\Sigma},\Sigma_{\mathbb{Z}}^{\prime},\Phi)$ will determine a ${{{\mathbb{F}}_{1}}}$-scheme with relations denoted by the quadruple $(\underline{\Sigma},\Sigma_{\mathbb{Z}},\Sigma_{\mathbb{Z}}^{\prime},\Phi)$.
Definition 2.6. [23, Def. 2.12] a) Let $\Xi$ be an affine scheme in ${\mathsf{Aff}}_{\mathsf{C}}$. A subsheaf ${\mathcal{F}}\subset\Xi$ is said to be a Zariski open of $\Xi$ if there exists a collection of open Zariski immersions $\{\Xi_{i}\to\Xi\}_{i\in I}$ such that ${\mathcal{F}}$ is the image of the sheaf morphism $\coprod_{i\in I}\Xi_{i}\to\Xi$. (b) A morphism ${\mathcal{F}}\to{\mathcal{G}}$ in ${\mathsf{Sh}}^{\text{Zar}}({\mathsf{Aff}}_{\mathsf{C}})$ is said to be an open Zariski immersion if, for any affine scheme $\Xi$ and any sheaf morphism $\Xi\to{\mathcal{G}}$, the induced morphism ${\mathcal{F}}\times_{{\mathcal{G}}}\Xi\to\Xi$ is a monomorphism whose image is a Zariski open of $\Xi$. (c) Let ${\mathcal{F}}$ be a sheaf in ${\mathsf{Sh}}^{\text{Zar}}({\mathsf{Aff}}_{\mathsf{C}})$. A collection of open Zariski immersions $\{\Xi_{i}\to{\mathcal{F}}\}_{i\in I}$, where each $\Xi_{i}$ is an affine scheme over ${\mathsf{Aff}}_{\mathsf{C}}$, is said to be an affine Zariski cover of ${\mathcal{F}}$ if the resulting morphism $\coprod_{i\in I}\Xi_{i}\to{\mathcal{F}}$ is a sheaf epimorphism.
Definition 5.2. Given a scheme $\Sigma$ of ${\mathsf{Sch}}_{\mathsf{B}}$, we set • $\Sigma_{\mathbb{Z}}:=\widehat{F}_{\mathbb{Z}}(\Sigma)$, which is an object of ${\mathsf{Sch}}_{\mathsf{Ab}}$ (i.e. a classical scheme); • $\underline{\Sigma}:=\widehat{\rho}(\Sigma)$, which is an object of ${\mathsf{Sch}}_{{\mathsf{Set}}_{\ast}}$ (i.e. a monoidal scheme). We will say that the pair $(\underline{\Sigma},\Sigma_{\mathbb{Z}})$ is generated by the ${\mathsf{B}}$-scheme $\Sigma$.
Definition A.5 ([25], Def. 3.10). A pseudo-functor $\Pi\colon{\mathsf{C}}^{\mathrm{op}}\to\mathsf{Cat}$ consists of the following data: i) for each object $U$ of ${\mathsf{C}}$, a category $\Pi U$; ii) for each arrow $f\colon U\rightarrow V$, a functor $f^{\ast}\colon\Pi V\rightarrow\Pi U$; iii) for each object $U$ of ${\mathsf{C}}$, an isomorphism $\epsilon_{U}\colon Id^{\ast}_{U}\simeq id_{\Pi U}$ of functors $\Pi U\rightarrow\Pi U$; iv) for each pair of arrows $U\overset{f}{\rightarrow}V\overset{g}{\rightarrow}W$, an isomorphism $\alpha_{f,g}:f^{\ast}g^{\ast}\simeq(gf)^{\ast}\colon\Pi W\rightarrow\Pi U$ of functors $\Pi W\rightarrow\Pi U$. These data are required to satisfy some natural compatibility conditions which we do not explicitly describe here(see [25, p. 47]).
Definition 3.3. The category ${\mathsf{Blp}}$ is the full subcategory of $\,\text{-}\,\otimes_{{{\mathbb{F}}_{1}}}{\mathbb{N}}/{\mathsf{SRing}}$ whose objects $(A,A\otimes_{{{\mathbb{F}}_{1}}}{\mathbb{N}}\to R)$ satisfy the conditions: $\begin{array}[]{l}\text{a) the morphism $A\otimes_{{{\mathbb{F}}_{1}}}{\mathbb% {N}}\to R$ is an epimorphism;}\\ \text{b) the composition\ }A\to|A\otimes_{{{\mathbb{F}}_{1}}}{\mathbb{N}}|\to|% R|\text{, is a monomorphism}\\ \text{\phantom{b)}(the first map being the unit of the adjunction).}\end{array}$
Definition A.1 ([25], Def. 3.1). Let $p_{\mathsf{F}}\colon{\mathsf{F}}\to{\mathsf{C}}$ be a functor. An arrow $\phi:\xi\rightarrow\eta$ of ${\mathsf{F}}$ is Cartesian with respect to $p_{\mathsf{F}}$ if, for any arrow $\psi\colon\zeta\rightarrow\eta$ in $\mathcal{F}$ and any arrow $h\colon p_{{\mathsf{F}}}\zeta\rightarrow p_{{\mathsf{F}}}\xi$ in ${\mathsf{C}}$ with $p_{{\mathsf{F}}}\phi\circ h=p_{{\mathsf{F}}}\psi$, there exists a unique arrow $\theta\colon\zeta\rightarrow\xi$ with $p_{{\mathsf{F}}}\theta=h$ and $\phi\circ\theta=\psi$, as in the following diagram: $\xymatrix{\zeta\ar[rrr]^{\psi}\ar[rrd]_{\theta}\ar[dd]&&&\eta\ar[dd]\\ &&\xi\ar[ru]_{\phi}\ar[dd]\\ p_{\mathcal{F}}\zeta\ar^{\prime}[rr][rrr]\ar[rrd]_{h}&&&p_{\mathcal{F}}\eta\\ &&p_{\mathcal{F}}\xi\ar[ru]}$ Whenever $\xi\rightarrow\eta$ is a Cartesian arrow of ${\mathsf{F}}$ mapping to an arrow $U\rightarrow V$ of ${\mathsf{C}}$, we shall also say that $\xi$ is a pullback of $\eta$ to $U$.
Definition 2.7. A scheme over the category ${\mathsf{C}}$ is a sheaf ${\mathcal{F}}$ in ${\mathsf{Sh}}^{\text{Zar}}({\mathsf{Aff}}_{\mathsf{C}})$ that admits an affine Zariski cover. The category of schemes over ${\mathsf{C}}$ will be denoted by ${\mathsf{Sch}}_{\mathsf{C}}$.
Definition 5.3. [1, Def. 4.7] An ${{\mathbb{F}}_{1}}$-scheme is a triple $(\underline{\Xi},\Xi_{\mathbb{Z}},\Phi)$, where (1) $\underline{\Xi}$ is a monoidal scheme; (2) $\Xi_{\mathbb{Z}}$ is a (classical) scheme; (3) $\Phi$ is natural transformation $\underline{\Xi}\to\Xi_{\mathbb{Z}}\circ(\,\text{-}\,\otimes_{{{\mathbb{F}}_{1}% }}{\mathbb{Z}})$, such that the induced natural transformation $\underline{\Xi}\circ|\,\text{-}\,|\to\Xi_{\mathbb{Z}}$, when evaluated on fields, gives isomorphisms (of sets).¶In [1] the functor $\,\text{-}\,\otimes_{{{\mathbb{F}}_{1}}}{\mathbb{Z}}$ is denoted by $\beta$ and its right adjoint $|\,\text{-}\,|$ by $\beta^{\ast}$.
Definition A.8. Given a site ${\mathsf{C}}$, a fibered category $p_{\mathsf{F}}:{\mathsf{F}}\to{\mathsf{C}}$ is said to be i) a prestack if, for any object $U$ of ${\mathsf{C}}$ and covering $\mathcal{U}$ of $U$, the restriction functor $\operatorname{Hom}_{\mathsf{C}}({\mathsf{C}}_{/U},{\mathsf{F}})\to% \operatorname{Hom}_{\mathsf{C}}({\mathsf{C}}_{/\mathcal{U}},{\mathsf{F}})$ is an embedding; ii) a stack if, for any object $U$ of ${\mathsf{C}}$ and covering $\mathcal{U}$ of $U$, the restriction functor $\operatorname{Hom}_{\mathsf{C}}({\mathsf{C}}_{/U},{\mathsf{F}})\to% \operatorname{Hom}_{\mathsf{C}}({\mathsf{C}}_{/\mathcal{U}},{\mathsf{F}})$ is an equivalence.
Definition. A blueprint is a pair $B=(R,A)$, where $R$ is a semiring and $A$ is a multiplicative subset of $R$ containing $0$ and $1$ and generating $R$ as a semiring. A blueprint morphism $f\colon B_{1}=(R_{1},A_{1})\to B_{2}=(R_{2},A_{2})$ is a semiring morphism $f\colon R_{1}\to R_{2}$ such that $f(A_{1})\subset A_{2}$.
